A blockchain intelligence engineer is a specialist who analyzes blockchain data to uncover insights, detect risks and support investigations or analytics. This role combines blockchain technology, data science and cybersecurity skills.

Think of them as a mix of:

Blockchain researcher

Data analyst

Cyber intelligence analyst

They help understand what is happening on blockchains and who might be behind activity.

What they do

Common responsibilities include:

Tracking crypto transfers across wallets and blockchains

Detecting fraud, hacks, scams and money laundering

Using on chain analytics tools to trace transactions

Building dashboards and models for blockchain activity

Supporting law enforcement or compliance teams

Researching protocols, token movements and wallet behavior

Identifying trends in DeFi, NFTs or crypto ecosystems

Some work to stop bad actors. Others help funds and companies make decisions.

Skills needed

A blockchain intelligence engineer usually knows:

Blockchain fundamentals

Smart contracts (Solidity or Rust often)

Python and SQL

Data analysis and visualization

Graph analytics

Cybersecurity basics

On chain analytics platforms (for example Chainalysis, TRM Labs, Nansen, Arkham, Dune)

Where they work

You will find them in:

Crypto analytics companies

Blockchain security firms

Crypto exchanges

Government and law enforcement agencies

Hedge funds and venture funds

Web3 startups

Salary expectation

Depends on region and experience, but ranges roughly from entry to senior level:

Entry ~ 80k to 120k USD per year

Mid ~ 120k to 180k USD per year

Senior ~ 180k plus and bonuses in crypto firms

Simple explanation

A blockchain intelligence engineer studies blockchain data to track activity, find patterns and stop crime or support decisions.

